Course Title: Probability & Statistics for Machine Learning & Data Science
Course Info: Describe and quantify the uncertainty inherent in predictions made by machine learning modelsVisually and intuitively understand the properties of commonly used probability distributions in machine learning and data scienceApply common statistical methods like maximum likelihood estimation (MLE) and maximum a priori estimation (MAP) to machine learning problemsAssess the performance of machine learning models using interval estimates and margin of errors  Probability And Statistics, Machine Learning (ML) Algorithms, Statistical Analysis, Probability, Statistical Hypothesis Testing Week 1 - Introduction to Probability and Probability Distributions, Week 2 - Describing probability distributions and probability distributions with multiple variables, Week 3 - Sampling and Point estimation, Week 4 - Confidence Intervals and Hypothesis testing Computer Science
Course Info Translate: In this course, you will learn how to describe and quantify the uncertainty present in predictions made by machine learning models. You will also visually and intuitively understand the properties of commonly used probability distributions in machine learning and data science. Additionally, you will learn how to apply common statistical methods such as maximum likelihood estimation (MLE) and maximum a priori estimation (MAP) to machine learning problems. Furthermore, you will learn how to assess the performance of machine learning models using interval estimates and margin of errors. This course covers topics such as Probability And Statistics, Machine Learning (ML) Algorithms, Statistical Analysis, Probability, and Statistical Hypothesis Testing. The course is divided into four weeks: Week 1 - Introduction to Probability and Probability Distributions, Week 2 - Describing probability distributions and probability distributions with multiple variables, Week 3 - Sampling and Point estimation, Week 4 - Confidence Intervals and Hypothesis testing in Computer Science.
Course Title Translate: Probability & Statistics for Machine Learning & Data Science

Course Info: Explain the difference between legacy payment systems and new innovations in payments.Describe blockchain technology and critique its application in various contexts.Interpret a credit score and identify its determinants.Implement “smart” investing techniques. Payment Systems, Cryptocurrency, Credit Technology, Smart Investing, Blockchain The Future of Payment Technologies, Blockchain and Cryptocurrency Explained, Raising Capital: Credit Tech, Coin Offerings, and Crowdfunding, Innovations in Investment Technology: Artificial Intelligence Computer Science
Course Info Translate:
Legacy payment systems refer to traditional methods of transferring money, such as cash, checks, and credit cards. These systems have been in place for many years and are often slow and costly. On the other hand, new innovations in payments, such as mobile wallets and cryptocurrencies, offer faster, cheaper, and more secure ways to make transactions.

Blockchain technology is a decentralized and secure way of recording transactions across a network of computers. It has the potential to revolutionize various industries by providing transparency, security, and efficiency. However, its application in some contexts may face challenges such as scalability and regulatory issues.

A credit score is a numerical representation of an individual's creditworthiness, based on their credit history and financial behavior. The determinants of a credit score include payment history, credit utilization, length of credit history, types of credit used, and new credit accounts.

Implementing "smart" investing techniques involves using data, technology, and research to make informed investment decisions. This can include strategies such as diversification, asset allocation, and risk management.

Overall, the future of payment technologies, blockchain, and cryptocurrency are promising, but it is important to understand their implications and potential risks. Additionally, advancements in credit technology and investment technology, such as artificial intelligence and computer science, are shaping the way we manage our finances and make investment decisions.

Course Info Translate: Rate Monotonic theory is a method used to analyze real-time systems and design techniques. It involves engineering principles for allocating functionality and services to hardware, firmware, or software implementation. Other concepts include fault tolerance, real-time operating systems (RTOS), Linux on embedded systems, and asymmetric multi-core processing. This theory also covers real-time embedded systems concepts and practices, as well as the design of mission-critical systems. It is a key component in computer science projects involving embedded systems.

Course Info Translate:
In order to achieve success as a product manager, it is important to understand the roles, responsibilities, skills, competencies, and knowledge requirements associated with the position. This includes examining the entire product management lifecycle and the crucial role that a product manager plays in driving the success of a product. It is also important to investigate the concept of "value creation" and how a product manager can contribute to adding value to a product.

Additionally, it is beneficial to compare and contrast different career paths within product management and consider obtaining certifications that can help advance your career in the field. Some relevant topics to explore include Product Management, Value Proposition, Product Management Lifecycle, ProdBOK Product Manager Profession Overview, The Product Lifecycle and the Product Manager, Product Management Fundamentals, Product Management Opportunities and Certifications, Final Project, Assessment and Course Wrap-up in the field of Computer Science.

Course Info Translate: Design thinking is a problem-solving approach that involves user-centered design, prototyping, and addressing social issues. Before beginning the design thinking process, it is important to ask questions such as "What is?" and "What if?" in order to foster a mindset for innovation. Additionally, it is important to ask "What wows?" and "What works?" in order to determine the best ideas to pursue.

Course Title: Linear Regression in R for Public Health
Course Info: Describe when a linear regression model is appropriate to useRead in and check a data set's variables using the software R prior to undertaking a model analysis    Fit a multiple linear regression model with interactions, check model assumptions and interpret the output      Correlation And Dependence, Linear Regression, R Programming INTRODUCTION TO LINEAR REGRESSION, Linear Regression in R, Multiple Regression and Interaction, MODEL BUILDING Computer Science
Course Info Translate: Linear regression is appropriate to use when there is a linear relationship between the dependent and independent variables. In order to analyze a data set using a linear regression model, it is important to first read in and check the variables using the software R. After this, a multiple linear regression model with interactions can be fitted, model assumptions can be checked, and the output can be interpreted. This process helps in understanding the correlation and dependence between variables, and is a key aspect of model building in computer science.
Course Title Translate: Linear Regression in R for Public Health

Course Title: Probability & Statistics for Machine Learning & Data Science
Course Info: Describe and quantify the uncertainty inherent in predictions made by machine learning modelsVisually and intuitively understand the properties of commonly used probability distributions in machine learning and data scienceApply common statistical methods like maximum likelihood estimation (MLE) and maximum a priori estimation (MAP) to machine learning problemsAssess the performance of machine learning models using interval estimates and margin of errors  Probability And Statistics, Machine Learning (ML) Algorithms, Statistical Analysis, Probability, Statistical Hypothesis Testing Week 1 - Introduction to Probability and Probability Distributions, Week 2 - Describing probability distributions and probability distributions with multiple variables, Week 3 - Sampling and Point estimation, Week 4 - Confidence Intervals and Hypothesis testing DataScience
Course Info Translate: In this course, you will learn to describe and quantify the uncertainty present in predictions made by machine learning models. You will also visually and intuitively understand the properties of commonly used probability distributions in machine learning and data science. Additionally, you will learn to apply common statistical methods such as maximum likelihood estimation (MLE) and maximum a priori estimation (MAP) to machine learning problems. You will also be able to assess the performance of machine learning models using interval estimates and margins of error. The topics covered in this course include Probability and Statistics, Machine Learning (ML) Algorithms, Statistical Analysis, Probability, and Statistical Hypothesis Testing. The course is divided into four weeks: Week 1 - Introduction to Probability and Probability Distributions, Week 2 - Describing probability distributions and probability distributions with multiple variables, Week 3 - Sampling and Point estimation, Week 4 - Confidence Intervals and Hypothesis testing.
Course Title Translate: Probability & Statistics for Machine Learning & Data Science

Course Info: Play with 50 algorithmic puzzles on your smartphone to develop your algorithmic intuition!  Apply algorithmic techniques (greedy algorithms, binary search, dynamic programming, etc.) and data structures (stacks, queues, trees, graphs, etc.) to solve 100 programming challenges that often appear at interviews at high-tech companies. Get an instant feedback on whether your solution is correct.Apply the newly learned algorithms to solve real-world challenges: navigating in a Big Network  or assembling a genome of a deadly pathogen from millions of short substrings of its DNA.Learn exactly the same material as undergraduate students in “Algorithms 101” at top universities and more! We are excited that students from various parts of the world are now studying our online materials in the Algorithms 101 classes at their universities. Here is a quote from the website of Professor Sauleh EetemadiOpens in a new tab from Iran University of Science and Technology: “After examining syllabus and course material from top universities including StanfordOpens in a new tab, PrincetonOpens in a new tab and MITOpens in a new tab we have chosen to follow the Data Structures and Algorithms SpecializationOpens in a new tab from UCSD...due to excellent course material and its practical approach.”If you decide to venture beyond Algorithms 101, try to solve more complex programming challenges (flows in networks, linear programming, streaming algorithms, etc.) and complete an equivalent of a graduate course in algorithms! Course Info Translate: You will learn the basics to create a program in Python and recognize the main commands. Use artificial neural networks for classification, segmentation, and object detection.
